miscontrue\/\/interpret in the wrong way\/\/con lau moi dung\/\/The politician never trusted journalists because he thought that they miscontrue his words and misrepresent his positions.

craven\/\/pathetically cowardly\/\/ra vuon\/\/Though the man could have at least alerted the police, he crouched cravenly in the corner as the old woman was mugged.

capricious\/\/determined by chance or impulse or whim rather than by necessity or reason\/\/cha co ri chuan\/\/Nearly every month our capricious CEO had a new plan to turn the company around, and none of them worked because we never gave them the time they needed to succeed.

ignominious\/\/(Used of conduct or character) deserving or bringing disgrace or shame.\/\/nhuc me no\/\/Since the politician preached ethics and morality, his texting of revealing photographs was ignominious bringing shame on both himself and his party

dilatory\/\/wasting time\/\/delay\/\/Lawyers use dilatory tactics so that it takes years before the case is actually decided.

maladroit\/\/clumsy\/\/may la droid\/\/As a child, she was quite maladroid, but as an adult, she has become an adept dancer

deleterious\/\/harmful to living things\/\/delete\/\/The BP oil spill in the Gulf of Mexico was deleterious to the fishing insdustry in the southern states.

indecorous\/\/not in keeping with accepted standards of what is right or proper in polite society\/\/not decorous\/\/Eating with elbows on the table is considered indecorous in refined circles.

duress\/\/compulsory force or threat\/\/\/\/The witness said he signed the contract under duress and argued that the court should concel the agreement.
